The '''[[2014–15 NHL season|2014–15]] [[San Jose Sharks]] season''' was the [[List of San Jose Sharks seasons|24th]] season in the [[National Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite book |last=National Hockey League|title=The National Hockey League Official Guide & Record Book/2014|year=2013 |publisher= Diamond Sports Data, Inc. |page=117|isbn= 978-1-894801-26-3}}</ref> The Sharks did not qualify for the [[2015 Stanley Cup playoffs]], thus ending their ten-season playoff streak.

==Off-season==
On May 15, 2014, following a first round playoff loss to the [[Los Angeles Kings]], General Manager [[Doug Wilson (ice hockey)|Doug Wilson]] made known his intentions to build a "younger, more aggressive team", announcing that the team would retain Head Coach [[Todd McLellan]], but will move 33-year-old winger [[Martin Havlát|Martin Havlat]], who still had one year on remaining his contract, and would not re-sign 37-year-old impending unrestricted free agent defenceman [[Dan Boyle (ice hockey)|Dan Boyle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sharks.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=719659|title=Parting with Boyle, Havlat; Burns Back to D|publisher=Sharks.nhl.com|accessdate=December 21, 2014}}</ref> The Sharks also acquired [[John Scott (ice hockey)|John Scott]] and [[Tye McGinn]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mercurynews.com/sharks/ci_26076577/sharks-sign-free-agent-enforcer-john-scott | title=Sharks sign free-agent enforcer John Scott, trade for Tye McGinn | accessdate=11 March 2015 | author=Pashelka, Curtis}}</ref>

==Regular season==
The Sharks did not qualify for the [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] for the first time since [[2002–03 San Jose Sharks season|2002–03]], ending the second-longest active [[List of NHL franchise post-season appearance streaks|NHL playoff appearance streak]] at ten seasons.

